Class AbstractTypeMatcher

java.lang.Object
org.microbean.assign.AbstractTypeMatcher
All Implemented Interfaces:
Constable, BiPredicate<TypeMirror,TypeMirror>, Matcher<TypeMirror,TypeMirror>
public abstract class AbstractTypeMatcher extends Object implements Constable, Matcher<TypeMirror,TypeMirror>
A partial implementation of a Matcher that tests if one TypeMirror matches another.

This class consists primarily of utility methods useful for assisting in implementing type matching according to a variety of rules, such as those described or implemented by CDI or the Spring framework.

Author:
Laird Nelson

    • covariantlyAssignable

      protected boolean covariantlyAssignable(TypeMirror receiver, TypeMirror payload)
      Returns true if and only if payload is covariantly assignable to receiver.

      The default implementation of this method returns the result of invoking Domain.assignable(TypeMirror, TypeMirror) on the return value of an invocation of the domain() method, supplying the two arguments in reverse order.

      Parameters:
      receiver - a TypeMirror; must not be null; the "left hand side" of the putative assignment
      payload - a TypeMirror; must not be null; the "right hand side" of the putative assignment
      Returns:
      true if and only if payload is covariantly assignable to receiver
      Throws:
      NullPointerException - if either argument is null
      See Also:
      • Domain.assignable(TypeMirror, TypeMirror)

    • describeConstable

      public Optional<? extends ConstantDesc> describeConstable()
      Returns an Optional housing a ConstantDesc that represents this AbstractTypeMatcher implementation.

      This method never returns null.

      The default implementation of this method relies on the presence of a public constructor that accepts a single Domain-typed argument.

      The Optional returned by an invocation of this method may be, and often will be, empty.

    • identical

      protected boolean identical(TypeMirror receiver, TypeMirror payload)
      A utility method that returns true if and only if this AbstractTypeMatcher implementation considers the two supplied TypeMirrors to be identical.

      The default implementation returns true if receiver is literally the very same Java object reference as payload, or if an invocation of Domain.sameType(TypeMirror, TypeMirror) with the two arguments returns true.

      (As an arbitrary counterexample, Spring relies on the equals method of java.lang.reflect.Type, whose behavior is effectively undefined.)

      Parameters:
      receiver - a TypeMirror; must not be null
      payload - a TypeMirror; must not be null
      Returns:
      true if and only if this AbstractTypeMatcher implementation considers the two supplied TypeMirrors to be identical; false otherwise
      Throws:
      NullPointerException - if either argument is null
      See Also:
      • Domain.sameType(TypeMirror, TypeMirror)
